   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "8de06875-f830-41d7-8c73-c90a5d6f784d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Axes: >"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 18,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sns.boxplot(df)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "ba6968d1-d65a-46c4-a797-34cc704457b2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#Removing outliers using IQR method\n",
    "\n",
    "def outliers(df):\n",
    "    for col in df.select_dtypes(include = 'float64').columns:\n",
    "        Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)\n",
    "        Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)\n",
    "        IQR = Q3 - Q1\n",
    "        Lower = Q1 -(1.5* IQR)\n",
    "        Upper = Q3 + (1.5 * IQR)\n",
    "        # capping\n",
    "        df[col] = df[col].apply(lambda x : Lower if x < Lower else Upper if x > Upper else x)\n",
    "    return df"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "id": "4b465c58-96e1-4b58-b9e9-d0cca8c3d1c4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#assigning df2 as outliers removed data\n",
    "\n",
    "df2=outliers(df)"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "393932e3-ee9e-4321-a852-db5366a2ac27",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Between -0.5 and 0.5 are considered fairly symmetrical.\n",
    "### Between -1 and -0.5 or 0.5 and 1 are moderately skewed.\n",
    "### Less than -1 or greater than 1 indicate high skewness."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "id": "f8edede2-ee96-4700-adf2-7c0bef855af6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#Applying power transformer transformation to remove skewness\n",
    "\n",
    "pt=PowerTransformer(method='yeo-johnson')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   ]

   "source": [
    "# Train and evaluate each model\n",
    "for name, model in models.items():\n",
    "    print(f\"\\nTraining {name}...\")\n",
    "    #Fitting Model\n",
    "    model.fit(x_train, y_train)\n",
    "    #Make the Prediction\n",
    "    y_pred = model.predict(x_test)\n",
    "    #Evaluate the model\n",
    "    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)\n",
    "    results[name]= {\n",
    "        'model': model,\n",
    "        'accuracy': accuracy,\n",
    "        'report': classification_report(y_test, y_pred)\n",
    "    }\n",
    "    print(f\" {name} Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}\")\n",
    "    print(\"\\nClassification Report:\")\n",
    "    print(results[name]['report'])"
   ]
  },

    "# Best Model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c103ef59-7da5-4bd4-bdf0-621fe94f6abb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Logistic Regression is the best model among all\n",
    "with accuracy : 0.9825\n",
    "\n",
    "Logistic Regression is a statistical method used for binary classification, where the outcome is either 0 or 1. It uses the sigmoid function to transform linear combinations of input features into probabilities, helping to predict the likelihood of an event occurring. Unlike linear regression, which provides continuous outputs, logistic regression outputs values between 0 and 1, making it ideal for classification tasks such as spam detection, medical diagnosis, and credit risk assessment. It is easy to implement, interpretable, and works well for linearly separable data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8cd4a4e9-bada-49f4-8369-f49853d04da6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Worst Performing Model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e04c67ce-42fe-4264-8763-b555c09266e3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Decision Tree Classifier is the worst model among all\n",
    "with accuracy : 0.9474\n",
    "\n",
    "A Decision Tree classifier can be one of the worst models because it tends to overfit the training data, making it perform poorly on new, unseen data. It creates overly complex trees that capture noise instead of true patterns, leading to high variance. Decision trees are also sensitive to small changes in data, which can drastically alter their structure. Additionally, they struggle with imbalanced datasets and do not generalize well without pruning or ensemble methods like Random Forest. Due to these weaknesses, they are often outperformed by more robust models like logistic regression, support vector machines, or neural networks."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a95a4c4e-6d55-4a81-accb-62ea1977629d",
